The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Sunday, August 01, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Calcutta, July 31: Police arrested 22-year-old Pinki Ghosh, daughter of an ONGC officer, for stealing gold jewellery worth Rs 60,000 over a year from the house of a girl she used to teach in Lake Town. 				 																																	Baffled by the disappearance of jewellery at regular intervals, timber merchant Satya Prakash Pande lodged a complaint. When police asked Pinki a few regular questions, there were discrepencies in her answers. Sleuths found she often visited two jewellery shops in Ultradanga and Nagerbazar. Confronted by the police, Pinki confessed, saying she needed the money. 				 																																	Calcutta/Howrah: Amalendu Bikash Saha and his wife Arati, named in the letter of Shibendu Saha, who murdered six members of his family and committed suicide, were remanded in judicial custody for another 14 days. The four suspects in the Kuntal Sain murder case in Howrah were also remanded in judicial custody for a similar period. 				 																																	Calcutta: Goutam Ghosh, 40, was killed when a truck hit his motorcycle at Sukia Street around 9.30 pm. He was returning to his Sonarpur home. Ghosh died in hospital. 				 																																	Belpahari (West Midnapore): The Centre is planning to set up a Rs 25,000-crore fund for tribal people in seven states, including Bengal, said Union water resources minister Priya Ranjan Das Munshi, who visited Amlashol village, where five persons are said to have died of starvation.
